### Notes

*   **a.** **<sup>^</sup>** This is a consequence of the [Born rule](/Born_rule). The probability of observing an outcome upon [measurement](/Quantum_measurement) is the [modulus squared](/Modulus_squared) of the [probability amplitude](/Probability_amplitude) for that outcome. The global phase factor ${\displaystyle e^{i\delta }}$ is not measurable because it applies to both basis states and, being on the complex [unit circle](/Unit_circle), its modulus squared is always 1: ${\displaystyle {|e^{i\delta }|}^{2}=1.}$ Note that removing ${\displaystyle e^{i\delta }}$ means that [quantum states](/Quantum_state) that differ only by a global phase cannot be distinguished as distinct points on the surface of the Bloch sphere.
*   **b.** **<sup>^</sup>** While the relative phase has no effect on measurements in the computational basis (the Pauli Z basis), it is crucial when [measuring](/Quantum_measurement) in other bases, like the X or Y Pauli basis. For example, the state ${\displaystyle ({|0\rangle }+e^{i\pi /2}{|1\rangle })/{\sqrt {2}}}$ (which lies on the positive pole of the Y-axis) will always be measured to the same value in the Y-basis. In the Z-basis, however, it has an equal probability of being measured as ${\displaystyle {|0\rangle }}$ or ${\displaystyle {|1\rangle }}$. Because measurement [collapses](/Wave_function_collapse) the quantum state, measuring in one basis obscures information that would have been accessible in another, a direct manifestation of the [uncertainty principle](/Uncertainty_principle).

#